source.689b36b4: ### Collaborative Filtering: Collaborative filtering movie recommender systems are said to be more widely used and make recommendations to users based on the similarity between users, in this case it would be the recommendation of a movie or the likely prediction a user could rate a movie based on the ratings of similar users. Though they are widely used in the industry, one of the drawbacks of collaborative filtering is the so called `cold start problem` when it comes to new users, as the system does not have sufficient data on the user to make accurate predictions. Unlike content based methods, collaborative algorithms return more varied results, enabling the business to introduce users to new types of content, hence increasing viewage and profit. It is for this reason that we use Collaborative filtering as our main approach. The tested models are all implemented from sklean's `surprise` package. The algorithms are tested below and their results summarised in the table in the comet section.

source.35b0b198: ### **About Machine Learning and Recommender Systems** Machine Learning (ML) is a subset of Artificial Intelligence (AI), dating as far back as 1959, where computers are trained to pick up patterns and make decisions with little to no human interference. There are two main types, supervised and unsupervised learning. In contrast to supervised models, where the algorithm is given answers to train on, the unsupervised model processes unlabelled data (no answers) using various statistical techniques to detect and leverage the underlying patterns and distributions within the data. In this project, we will use scikit-learn's 'surprise' package to test various models on our data with the ultimate goal of selecting and optimising the model that most accurately predict labels for our data, in this case ratings for movies that users have not yet watched. A recommender system is an engine or platform capable of predicting the statistically most likely movie(s) that a user would like to watch. A pertinent example is the recommender system that the streaming giant [Netflix](https://www.netflix.com/za/) uses to suggest content to users to increase viewing time on their platform. The system uses all of the user generated data as actionable like-dislike information in their various recommender engines within the system. This type of input includes: - Time spent viewing per title (seconds - while scrolling). - What a user clicked on or watched a trailer for. - Personal attributes such as geographical location, religion, race, culture, poltical views, hobbies, and more. A recommender system enhances a user's experience since the convenience of personalised recommendations will save the user the time and effort of having to search through a large catalogue. This allows also exposes the user to new content, creating an opportunity for further increased viewing-time and hence revenue for the business.
source.5db00f69: ### **Comet Experiments Feedback** The accompanying image is of the successful experiments logged on to Comet: * The models of interest are the `NMF` as the worst performing at and RMSE score of `1.16`. ### **Dataset Descriptions** The supplied dataset comprises the following: 1. **genome_scores.csv** - A score mapping the strength between movies and tag-related properties 2. **train.csv** - The training split of the dataset. Contains user and movie IDs with associated rating data 3. **test.csv** - The test split of the dataset. Contains user and movie IDs with no rating data 4. **tags.csv** - User assigned for the movies within the dataset 5. **links.csv** - File providing a mapping between a movie ID, IMDB IDs and TMDB IDs 6. **movies** - File providing details about the title of the movie, genres and movieID that further can be used to merge to other related dataset 7. **imdb_data.csv** - Additional movie metadata scraped from IMDB using the links.csv file 8. **genome_tags.csv** - User assigned tags for genome-related scores
Note: The 'train' set contains the central data, to which the other sets are auxilliary (optional to include). You'll notice in this project we only used 'train' for predictive modelling due to considerations for hosting the final model online with limited computing resources.

### **Comet Instructions**
Note: Do not run any cell regarding comet as it will initiate an experiment. The experiments in this notebook have already been recorded.

- According to [techcrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2018/04/05/cometml-wants-to-do-for-machine-learning-what-github-did-for-code/#:~:text=Comet.ml%20allows%20data%20scientists,optimize%20their%20machine%20learning%20models.), Comet is a versioning platform that allows data scientists and developers alike to be able to track, make comparisons and optimisations to their machine learning models. Below is a guide on how to use Comet.
Step 1: Pip Install the `comet_ml` package. Step 2 : Import the `Experiment` class from the `comet_ml` package. Step 3: Create an instance of the `Experiment` class and copy and paste the `api_key`, `project_name`, `workspace` as found under the project on Comet (these have also been pasted in the cells below). Step 4: To run an experiment, run the code on one model at a time, this will serve as one experiment at a time. Step 5: A dictionary containing model params is created and saved on comet as logs. Step 6 : Close the expiriment. Note that upon initialising the experiment in the notebook, an experiment is automatically initialised on the comet page. This is how an experiment is linked real time to the notebook and the comet page. The same also applies upon closing an experiment. Columns can then be adjusted to show information deemed important, such as the name of algorithms used and their resulting metric scores, in this case RMSE scores, etc.
source.64c18394: ### Content Based: Content Based movie recommender systems suggest items based on similarity to a movie that they already positively rated/interacted with. In the context of movies, such a system could use features such as director, cast, genre or description of a movie to make recommendations. Though content-based filtering doesn't need any data about users to make recommendations, a drawback is it tends to return on average items in a similar category with little variation across the recommendations.
